// TEST: exec_cross_module_use
// EXPECT: output "result=21"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// Regression fixture for the codegen-completeness milestone (DV13): a user
// `module main` that `use`s symbols from a *second* user module, compiling and
// running on all five targets. This is a MULTI-FILE fixture — the `// FILE:`
// marker below declares the imported module `mathutil`; the harness writes it
// into the temp project alongside this entry module so the build's recursive
// `.bock` discovery compiles both, exercising the real cross-module `use` path.
//
// Before the fix, the five backends emitted a non-functional import for the
// `use` (js/ts a `// import` comment, python `from mathutil import ...`, rust
// `use mathutil::{...}`, go `import "mathutil"`) while each module was emitted
// as a *separate* file. The conformance harness and the build toolchain both
// compile + run a single `main.<ext>`, so the imported symbols were undefined
// / unresolved at run time on every target.
//
// The fix bundles every module the entry program actually `use`s (here:
// `mathutil` + `main`, in dependency order) into the one entry file and drops
// the `ImportDecl`s, so `add_one` and `triple` resolve against declarations
// concatenated into the same file. Modules reachable only via the implicit
// §18.2 prelude (the embedded `core.*` stdlib) are NOT bundled, so a program
// that uses no core symbol — like this one — emits exactly its own modules.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale). `mathutil`'s functions ARE `public`: cross-module
// `use` only resolves exported items.
module main

use mathutil.{add_one, triple}

fn main() -> Void {
  let a: Int = add_one(6)
  let b: Int = triple(a)
  println("result=${b}")
}

// FILE: mathutil.bock
module mathutil

public fn add_one(n: Int) -> Int {
  n + 1
}

public fn triple(n: Int) -> Int {
  n * 3
}
